    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so if its mostly hydrogen ions and not just lactic acid, what exactly is the process of them building up? like how do they actually get in there and cause that burning sensation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The buildup of hydrogen ions ($\\text{H}^+$) is a direct result of your muscles needing massive amounts of energy, which is primarily supplied by anaerobic respiration during those short, intense HIIT bursts. When oxygen supply can't keep up with the demand, your cells start breaking down glucose without enough oxygen, leading to the production of pyruvate, which then converts into lactate and releases those irritating hydrogen ions. These excess $\\text{H}^+$ ions lower the pH within the muscle cells, and this acidification is what your brain interprets as that intense, fiery burning sensation. It's a chemical signal telling your muscles, \"Hey, you're working too hard, slow down!\"",
      "source": "target",
